\subsection{Dissipativity and Existence of a Global Attractor}
Using the formal definition from \cite{Robinson2001}, we can show that discretized Asymptotic Lenia is a dissipative semiflow.  For some $\varepsilon > 0$, consider the compact set $\mathcal{B}_\varepsilon=[0-\varepsilon,1+\varepsilon]^{N^2} \subset \mathcal{X}$. Let $m(t)=\min_{i,j}A[i,j](t)$, $M(t)=\max_{i,j}A[i,j](t)$. If we choose the initial condition $A[i,j](0)\in \mathcal{X}$ and assume $0\le T(\cdot)\le 1$, we find:

\begin{align*}
    \frac{dM}{dt} &= T(K*A) - M \le 1 - M \\[4pt]
                  &\implies M(t) \le 1 + \bigl(M(0)-1\bigr)e^{-t} \\[8pt]
    \frac{dm}{dt} &= T(K*A) - m \ge -m \\[4pt]
                  &\implies m(t) \ge m(0)\,e^{-t}
\end{align*}

\noindent Therefore, after a finite time

\[
t^*= \max\left\{\ln\left|\frac{M(0)-1}{\varepsilon}\right|, \ln\left|\frac{m(0)}{\varepsilon}\right|\right\}
\]
we must have $A[i,j](t)\in \mathcal{B}_\varepsilon,\, \forall\, t \ge t^*$. We can conclude that there exists a global attractor $\mathcal{A}$. A very similar argument can be used to show that the full PDE is also dissipative, but this is not necessary for our purposes. We can now inquire about the kinds of behavior we expect to see on the attractor. 

\subsection{Helmholtz Decomposition and Behavior on the Attractor}
We can calculate the divergence of the discretized flow $\mathbf{F}[i,j](A)$ as follows:

% \begin{align*}
% \nabla_A \cdot \mathbf{F}[i,j](A) &= \sum_{i,j} \left(\frac{\partial}{\partial A[i,j]} \mathbf{F}[i,j](A)\right) \\
% &= \sum_{i,j} \left(\frac{\partial}{\partial A[i,j]} T\left(\sum_{k,l} A[k,l]\,K[i-k,j-l]\right) - \frac{\partial}{\partial A[i,j]} A[i,j]\right) \\
% &= \sum_{i,j} \left(K[0,0]\, T'\left(\sum_{k,l} A[k,l]\,K[i-k,j-l]\right) - 1\right) \\
% &= \sum_{i,j} -1 \\
% &= -N^2
% \end{align*}

\begin{align*}
\nabla_A \cdot \mathbf{F}&= \sum_{i,j} \frac{\partial}{\partial A[i,j]} \mathbf{F}[i,j](A) \\
&= \sum_{i,j} \left(\frac{\partial}{\partial A[i,j]} T((K*A)[i,j]) - \frac{\partial A[i,j]}{\partial A[i,j]}\right) \\
&= \sum_{i,j} \left(K[0,0]\, T'((K*A)[i,j]) - 1\right) \\
&= \sum_{i,j} -1 \\
&= -N^2
\end{align*}

Here we use the fact that $K[0,0]=0$ to show that the divergence comes entirely from the $-A$ term. This means that we can write the $\mathbf{F}$ as the sum of a divergence-free term and a term which is the gradient of a scalar potential [find citation]:
\[
\mathbf{F}[i,j](A) = \underbrace{T\left((K*A)[i,j]\right)}_{\text{divergence-free}} + \underbrace{\nabla_A \left[-\frac{1}{2} \sum_{k,l} A^2[k,l]\right]}_{\text{gradient}}
\]

Such a decomposition is known as a Helmholtz-Hodge decomposition \citep{hhd2013}. The decomposition is known to be unique if there is no net flux through the boundary of the domain. We proved earlier that if we start with $A[i,j](0)\in\mathcal{B}_\varepsilon$, then $A[i,j](t)\in\mathcal{B}_\varepsilon$ for all $t\ge 0$, so we can confirm that the decomposition is in fact unique if we choose this domain. Since the divergence-free component in the unique decomposition is not trivial, we can conclude that Asymptotic Lenia cannot be formulated as a pure gradient flow of any scalar potential.
